  "prompt_text": "Calculate the probability of getting exactly 3 heads in 5 coin flips of a fair coin.",
  "response_text": "To calculate the probability of getting exactly 3 heads in 5 coin flips, we can use the binomial probability formula. The binomial distribution is used to find the probability of obtaining a specific number of successes (heads) in a fixed number of trials (coin flips) when the probability of success (getting heads) is constant (0.5 for a fair coin).\n\nThe binomial probability formula is:\n\nP(X=k) = C(n, k) * (p^k) * ((1-p)^(n-k))\n\nwhere:\n- P(X=k) is the probability of k successes (heads) in n trials (coin flips)\n- C(n, k) is the number of combinations of n items taken k at a time, which can be calculated using the formula C(n, k) = n! / [k!(n-k)!]\n- p is the probability of success (getting heads)\n- n is the number of trials (coin flips)\n- k is the number of successes (heads) we want to find the probability for (in this case, 3)\n\nPlugging in the values for our problem:\n- n = 5 (total coin flips)\n- k = 3 (exactly 3 heads)\n- p = 0.5 (probability of getting heads)\n\nP(X=3) = C(5, 3) * (0.5^3) * ((1-0.5)^(5-3))\n\nFirst, let's calculate C(5, 3):\nC(5, 3) = 5! / [3!(5-3)!] = 10\n\nNow, we can calculate the probability:\nP(X=3) = 10 * (0.5^3) * ((1-0.5)^2) = 10 * 0.125 * 0.25 = 0.3125\n\nSo, the probability of getting exactly 3 heads in 5 coin flips is 0.3125 or 31.25%.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 10\nV (Verbal Fluency): 10\nG (Goal Directedness): 10\nP (Pattern Recognition): 10\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 10\nQ (Query Interpretation): 10\nC (Contextual Awareness): 10\nY (Affective Modeling): 0 (This question does not require affective modeling)\nF (Flex",
